        "rich_text_8DL9Df": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Intro",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Choosing an engagement ring is a major milestone, but knowing which hand and finger the engagement ring should be worn on often brings up confusion. Traditions vary around the world, and modern preferences have evolved, making it important to understand the meaning, history, and etiquette behind ring-wearing customs.</p><p>This complete guide breaks down everything you need to know about which hand engagement ring female traditions follow, the symbolism behind different fingers, cultural variations, and how to choose what feels right for you.<br/><br/></p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_bUfHBT": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Understanding the Traditional Hand for Wearing an Engagement Ring",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Understanding the Traditional Hand for Wearing an Engagement Ring</h2>",
            "custom_id": "understanding",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_M3RwCW": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "The Western Tradition",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h3>The Western Tradition</h3>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_with_text_y7GhFU": {
          "type": "image_with_text",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/Understanding_the_Traditional_Hand_for_Wearing_an_Engagement_Ring_500_X_800_4.jpg",
            "text": "<p>In many Western countries, women typically wear their engagement ring on the left hand, on the fourth finger. This follows the ancient belief in the <em>vena amoris</em>, a vein said to run directly from this finger to the heart.</p>",
            "layout_direction": "row",
            "reverse_layout": true,
